.INDEX <TITO <INTRODUCTION
.CENTER
<TITO
.CENTER
----
((<INTRODUCTION))
.FILL.JUST
.PARA
<TITO WAS DEVELOPED TO PROVIDE AN IMPROVED UTILITY FOR MAGNETIC
TAPE WORK ON THE <TYMCOM-X SYSTEMS. <TITO CAN READ <TEX FORMAT TAPES BUT IT
MAY HAVE TROUBLE READING THE OLDER '<FAILSA' FORMAT (<FAILSAFE IS DOCUMENTED ELSEWHERE).
<TITO CANNOT PERFORM ANY 'MAGNETIC TAPE CONVERSION' FUNCTIONS NOR HANDLE 
TAPES FROM ANYWHERE ELSE BUT THE <TYMCOM-X SYSTEMS.
.PARA
^IN ADDITION, <TITO ALLOWS THE OPERATOR TO VERIFY THAT CHECKSUMS AGREE -
A CERTAIN METHOD OF ASSURING THAT NONE OF THE FILE HAS CHANGED DURING
THE TRANSFER TO OR FROM TAPE. <TITO ALLOWS STORING OF A FILE ACROSS THE
PHYSICAL TAPE BOUNDARY AND HAS THE ABILITY TO CONTINUE A TAPE JOB
ON A DIFFERENT TAPE DEVICE THAN THE ONE INITIALLY ASSIGNED TO THE JOB.
^IT ALLOWS MORE SELECTIVITY IN DETERMINING WHICH FILES WILL BE
OPERATED UPON FOR SELECTED COMMANDS, AND HOW MUCH DETAIL TO TYPE OUT ON
THE OPERATOR'S TERMINAL FOR TAPE TO DISK AND DISK TO TAPE PROCEDURES.
<TITO IS BETTER ABLE TO RECOVER
FROM CERTAIN COMMON TAPE FORMAT ERRORS THAN EARLIER TAPE UTILITIES.
^FINALLY, THE PROGRAM WILL ACCEPT PREVIOUSLY
CREATED INDIRECT OR COMMAND FILE INPUTS. ^USE OF INDIRECT FILES, CAREFULLY
CREATED, IS A TECHNIQUE THAT CAN SAVE MUCH TIME FOR
EXPERIENCED OPERATORS.
.SKIP 30
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.INDEX <TITO <COMMAND <SUMMARY
.NOFILL.NOJUST
^^
((COMMAND SUMMARY))
.SKIP 1
COMMAND     FUNCTION
-------     --------
.SKIP 1
NEW TAPE     INITIALIZE TAPE SO STORES START AT BEGINNING OF TAPE.
APPEND       INITIALIZE TAPE SO STORES START AT LOGICAL END OF TAPE.
STORE        WRITES FILES FROM DISK TO TAPE.
RESTORE      READS TAPE AND COPIES FROM TAPE TO DISK.
DIRECTORY    PRINTS A DIRECTORY LISTING FROM THE TAPE.
TRANSLATE    SETS TABLE TO ALLOW FOR RESTORES WHEN TAPE
             AND DISK USER NAMES ARE DIFFERENT.
CUT AFTER    MAKES AN END OF TAPE MARK AFTER A SPECIFIED FILE.
UNTRANSLATE  CLEARS TRANSLATION TABLE.
WHERE        TYPES OUT THE LAST POSITION SCANNED ON THE TAPE.
COF          CHANGES OUTPUT FILE FOR SUBSEQUENT COMMAND.
REWIND       REWINDS THE TAPE; <NO RETURN TO COMMAND LEVEL UNTIL DONE.
RWNW         REWINDS TAPE AND RETURNS IMMEDIATELY TO COMMAND LEVEL.
UNLOAD       SAME A RWNW BUT ALSO UNLOADS THE TAPE.
HELP         PRINTS LIST OF VALID TITO COMMANDS.
?            SAME EFFECT AS HELP COMMAND.
QUIT         EXITS FROM TITO PROGRAM BACK TO EXEC.
SKIP         JUMPS OVER A SPECIFIED NUMBER OF SAVE SETS.
DEVICE       CHANGE DEVICE OR DENSITY FOR CURRENT JOB.
GET          RESTORES FILES TO UFD OF USER WHO IS RUNNING TITO.
MODE         PRINTS AND SETS CONDITIONS WHEREBY FILES ARE RESTORED;
             DETERMINES LEVEL OF HARDCOPY DESIRED FOR STORE AND RESTORE.
UPDATE       SETS SWITCH TO RESTORE USING DISK STORAGE ALREADY
             ALLOCATED TO A FILE.
NOUPDATE     TURNS OFF THE UPDATE SWITCH.
FAILON       THIS COMMAND SHOULD BE USED IF ATTEMPTING TO 
             READ A FAILSAFE FORMAT TAPE.
FAILOFF      TURNS OFF THE FAILON SWITCH.
.SKIP 20
\\
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.FILL.JUST
.INDEX <TITO <COMMAND <DESCRIPTION
.INDEX <TITO <COMMAND <FORMAT
((<COMMAND <DESCRIPTION))
.PARA
^THE PROGRAM WILL PROMPT FOR A DEVICE NAME WHICH MUST BE
OF THE FORM <FTAN (^FAST ^T^APE) WHERE ^N IS A DRIVE NUMBER.
^NEXT THE PROGRAM
WILL TYPE THE TRACKS AND DENSITY AVAILABLE FOR THAT DEVICE.
^WHEN USING A 9 TRACK DRIVE (ON MOST <PDP-10 TAPE JOBS), 
THEN A DENSITY OF 1600 OR 6250 BPI CAN BE USED. ^THE DEFAULT DENSITY
SHOULD BE 6250. ^FOR EACH JOB, <TITO WILL ALSO SUPPLY A DEVICE NAME WHICH WILL
APPEAR ON ANY DIRECTORY LISTINGS
FOR FILES WRITTEN ON THE TAPE. ^THIS FEATURE CAN BE USED 1) TO
TELL  WHERE  THE FILE WAS WRITTEN; (2) TO READ FILES WRITTEN
ON A BADLY SKEWED DRIVE; (3) TO INDICATE THAT  A  PARTICULAR
TAPE DRIVE IS COMPATIBILITY ERROR PRONE AND SHOULD BE WRITTEN UP
FOR <NOVADYNE (<FSC) TO CHECK OUT.
.PARA
^ALL <TITO COMMANDS AND KEYWORD MODIFIERS MAY  BE  ABBREVIATED
TO  THE  MININUM  NUMBER   OF  CHARACTERS  REQUIRED TO MAKE THE
THE   COMMAND   UNIQUE.    ^FOR  EXAMPLE,  <DIRECTORY  MAY  BE
ABBREVIATED "<DI" AND <DEVICE MAY BE ABBREVIATED  "<DE".   <TITO
WILL  ALWAYS  INFORM THE OPERATOR IF THE ABBREVIATION IS NOT
UNIQUE, FOR EXAMPLE, THE AMBIGUOUS ABBREVIATION "^D".
.PARA
^THE <HELP COMMAND LISTS IN SUMMARY FORM THE PROGRAM  COMMANDS
AND  THE PURPOSE OF EACH. ^IN ADDITION, ^HELP MAY BE TYPED IN
THE MIDDLE OF A MULTIPART  COMMAND  TO  OBTAIN  THE  OPTIONS THAT APPLY.
.SKIP 1
^^
.CENTER
COMMAND FORMAT PARTS
.CENTER
--------------------
\\
.PARA
^THE MOST OFTEN USED COMMANDS IN <TITO ARE <STORE, <RESTORE, <GET AND
<DIRECTORY. ^THERE ARE THREE GENERAL PARTS TO <TITO
COMMAND FORMAT: THE VERB, THE OBJECT AND THE MODIFIER.
<STORE USES ALL THREE PARTS WHILE <RESTORE, <GET AND <DIRECTORY USE THE
FIRST TWO PARTS.
.SKIP 1
.CENTER
1.
^THE FIRST PART OF  EACH  COMMAND  IS  THE  VERB  (<STORE,
<RESTORE, <GET, <DIRECTORY).
.SKIP 1
.LEFT MARGIN 10
<STORE IS USED TO WRITE FILES ON TAPE AND REQUIRES  TAPE
INITIALIZATION. ^IT IS USED FOR CUSTOMER TAPES, BACKUPS, ALL 
FILES AND TRANSFERS.
.SKIP 1
<RESTORE RETRIEVES FILES FROM TAPE AND  PLACES  THEM  IN
THEIR ORIGINAL DIRECTORIES, UNLESS SOME FORM OF TRANSLATION 
IS USED.
.SKIP 1
<GET FUNCTIONS THE SAME AS RESTORE, EXCEPT THAT THE TAPE
FILES ARE WRITTEN TO THE <TITO USER'S DIRECTORY.
^THIS IN EFFECT, IS USUALLY A TRANSLATION FROM ANY TAPE USER
INTO DIRECTORY (<OPER) ON DISK.
.SKIP 1
<DIRECTORY IS USED TO CREATE A LISTING OF FILE NAMES AND OTHER INFO
FROM A SPECIFIED MAGTAPE. ^UNLESS SOME FORM OF THE <COF COMMAND
IS USED, THE TAPE DIRECTORY WILL OUTPUT ON THE TERMINAL.
.LEFT MARGIN 7
.SKIP 5
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.INDEX <TITO <COMMAND <OBJECTS
.FILL.JUST
.CENTER
2.
^THE SECOND PART OF EACH COMMAND IS THE OBJECT. ^THIS MAY BE:
.SKIP 1
.LEFT MARGIN 10
(1) ^A LIST OF GLOBAL ACCOUNT NUMBERS  PRECEDED BY "^G", E.G.
^G1 OR ^G1-4 OR ^G1,4,6;
.SKIP 1
(2) ^A LIST OF USERNAMES, E.G. (<SYS), (<OPER) OR A LIST OF <PPN'S
E.G. [1,1],[1,4];
.SKIP 1
(3) ^A LIST OF FILENAMES PRECEDED BY A USERNAME OR <PPN, E.G.
<(OPER)A.X,B.X,C.X OR [1,4]<A.X,B.X,C.X;
.SKIP 1
(4) ^THE DIRECTIVE "<ALL" PRECEDED BY A USERNAME TO SELECT ALL
THE FILES BELONGING TO A USER, OR NOT PRECEDED BY A USERNAME
TO SELECT ALL FILES BELONGING TO ALL USERS; 
.SKIP 1
(5) ^A LIST OF FILE POSITIONS PRECEDED BY '^P' OR '_#', E.G.
_#1,3-5,14;
.SKIP 1
(6) ^AN INDIRECT FILE PRECEDED BY AN '@' SIGN.
.LEFT MARGIN 7
.NOTE
^POSITION NUMBERS ARE NOT  MEANINGFUL  TO  THE <STORE COMMAND.
.END NOTE
.INDENT 5
^FILENAMES, EXCEPT FOR THAT OF AN INDIRECT FILE, MAY  CONTAIN
WILD  CARD  CHARACTERS  "_#"  OR  "?"  TO  MATCH ANY FILENAME
CHARACTER, OR AN ASTERISK IN THE NAME OR  EXTENSION  PORTION
OF  THE  FILENAME (OR BOTH) TO MATCH ALL NAMES OR EXTENSIONS
(OR BOTH).
.SKIP 20
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.INDEX <TITO <COMMAND <MODIFIERS
.FILL.JUST
.CENTER
3.
^THE THIRD PART OF THE  COMMAND  IS  A  MODIFIER  TO  THE
SECOND  PART. ^A <STORE COMMAND MAY HAVE MORE THAN ONE MODIFIER.
^THE  FOLLOWING  MODIFIERS  ARE  AVAILABLE:  <TWICE,   <THRICE,
<CREATED <AFTER,  <CHANGED, AND <STARTING <WITH.  ^THE <TWICE, <THRICE
<CREATED <AFTER,  AND <CHANGED MODIFIERS ARE MEANINGFUL ONLY TO
<STORE.
.LEFT MARGIN 10
.SKIP 1
^THE <TWICE MODIFIER CAUSES <TITO TO  WRITE  TWO  SAVESETS
INSTEAD OF ONE IN THE <STORE COMMAND.
.SKIP 1
^THE <THRICE MODIFIER CAUSES <TITO TO WRITE THREE SAVESETS
INSTEAD OF ONE IN THE <STORE COMMAND.
.SKIP 1
^THE <CREATED <AFTER MODIFIER TAKES AS ITS OBJECT  A  DATE
EXPRESSED AS <HH:MM <DD <MON <YR, WHERE <HH:MM IS THE TIME
IN HOURS AND MINUTES, AND <DD <MON <YR IS THE
DAY-MONTH-YEAR. ^FILES  TO BE STORED ARE RESTRICTED TO
THOSE CREATED AFTER THE SPECIFIED TIME AND  DATE. ^THE
TIME  AND  DATE  MAY  BE  ABBREVIATED: ^IF ONLY <HH:MM IS
GIVEN, THE DATE DEFAULTS TO THE CURRENT DAY-MONTH-YEAR;
IF ONLY <HH:MM <DD  IS  GIVEN, THE DATE DEFAULTS TO THE
CURRENT MONTH-YEAR; IF ONLY <HH:MM <DD <MON IS GIVEN, THE
DATE DEFAULTS TO THE CURRENT YEAR.
.SKIP 1
^THE <CHANGED MODIFIER TAKES NO OBJECT AND SPECIFIES THAT
ALL FILES WHICH  HAVE THE "FILE CHANGED" BIT ON IN
WILL BE WRITTEN TO TAPE. ^NOTE THAT  THE  "FILE
CHANGED"    BIT   CAN   BE   TURNED   OFF   ONLY   BY   A
"<STORE <ALL <CHANGED"  OPERATION  (THE DAILY BACKUP).
^THE <CHANGED MODIFIER IS SPECIFYING FILES WHICH HAVE CHANGED
SINCE THE LAST BACKUP OPERATION.
.SKIP 1
^THE <STARTING <WITH MODIFIER TAKES USERNAME  OR  FILENAME
AS  AN  OBJECT AND BEGINS THE CURRENT OPERATION (<STORE,
<RESTORE, <GET,  <DIRECTORY)  AT  THE  SPECIFIED  USER  OR
FILENAME. ^IN THE CASE OF FILES SPLIT BETWEEN TAPES, THE PROGRAM
WILL REPORT THE FILENAME FOLLOWED BY PAGE NUMBER AND PARTIAL
CHECKSUM ENCLOSED IN ANGLE BRACKETS "_<>".
^IF THE FILE SPLIT SHOULD FAIL, YOU SHOULD RESTART THE STORE MANUALLY
ON THE NEXT TAPE, USING THIS MODIFIER TO STORE THE ENTIRE FILE ON
THE NEXT TAPE.
.NOTE
^THE USER HAS THE OPTION OF SETTING A '<NO <FAILSA' BIT IN THE <UFD
WHICH WILL EXEMPT THE ENTIRE DIRECTORY FROM ALL FILES AND BACKUP
STORES.
^THE PROGRAM WHICH ALLOWS THIS OPTION, <DMPUFD, WILL CAUSE A <TITO
MESSAGE
^^
"USERNAME XXXX IGNORED".
\\
^THIS OPTION IS USUALLY ONLY APPLIED TO CERTAIN <MAGNUM APPLICATIONS.
.END NOTE
