.INDEX <TITO <INITIALIZATION <COMMANDS
^^
.CENTER
INITIALIZATION FOR STORE JOBS
.CENTER
-----------------------------
\\
.PARA
^WITH THE EXCEPTION OF THE <CUT <AFTER COMMAND, WHICH  REQUIRES
CONFIRMATION, AND IS NOT RECOMMENDED EXCEPT AS A 'LAST RESORT',
A TAPE MAY NOT BE WRITTEN ON UNTIL IT HAS BEEN
INITIALIZED. ^THERE   ARE   TWO   METHODS   PROVIDED   FOR
INITIALIZING  TAPE. ^THESE ARE (A) THE <NEW <TAPE COMMAND; (B)
THE <APPEND COMMAND.
.SKIP 1
.LEFT MARGIN 10
^THE <NEW <TAPE COMMAND REWINDS THE TAPE TO LOAD POINT SO  THAT
THE  NEXT <STORE COMMAND WILL BEGIN WITH <SAVESET <NO.  1, <FILE
<NUMBER 1.
.SKIP 1
^THE <APPEND COMMAND SPACES THE TAPE OUT TO THE LOGICAL END OF TAPE.
^UNLESS <TITO  IS  CERTAIN  THAT  THE  TAPE  IS POSITIONED AT
LOGICAL END OF TAPE,  A < REWIND  IS  AUTOMATICALLY  ISSUED FIRST.
.SKIP 1
^^
.INDEX <TITO <TRANSLATION
.CENTER
TRANSLATION OF USERNAMES FOR RESTORES
.CENTER
-------------------------------------
\\
.PARA
^FREQUENTLY IT IS NECESSARY TO RESTORE FILES  TO  A  USER  ON
DISC  WHICH  DIFFERS FROM THE USER ON TAPE. ^THE <GET COMMAND
DOES THIS FOR ONE USER (RESTORING FILES TO USERNAME RUNNING <TITO),
BUT OFTEN SEVERAL USERNAMES ARE INVOLVED AND THE RESTORE DESTINATION
IS DIFFERENT FROM THE USERNAME RUNNING <TITO. ^FOR THIS FUNCTION
THE <TRANSLATION COMMAND IS USED. ^IT SETS UP A TABLE OF DESTINATION
USER NAMES AND PRIOR TO RESTORING, <TITO SUBSTITUTES THE USERNAME IN
THE TRANSLATION TABLE FOR THE USERNAME ON TAPE.
.NOTE
^ALL USERNAMES NOT REFERENCED BY THIS TRANSLATION TABLE WILL BE SKIPPED
DURING SUBSEQUENT <TITO COMMANDS. ^ALSO, <TEX FORMAT TAPES WHICH DO
NOT USE USERNAMES WILL ALSO BE SKIPPED. ^IT IS RECOMMENDED YOU SET <MODE
<RESTORE <FILES (DESCRIBED LATER) WHENEVER YOU <TRANSLATE.
.END NOTE
.LEFT MARGIN 10
.SKIP 1
^THE TRANSLATION TABLE MAY BE  SET  UP BY USING THE
<TRANSLATE COMMAND AND THEN ENTERING THE DISC USERNAME AND TAPE USERNAME
SEPERATED BY A BACK ARROW OR UNDERSCORE CHARACTER.
.SKIP 1
^ALTERNATELY, DISK/TAPE USERNAME PAIRS MAY BE INCLUDED AS PART OF THE
<RESTORE OR <GET COMMAND STRINGS.
^FOR EXAMPLE, THE FOLLOWING COMMAND IS PRESENTED:
^^
.SKIP 1
"*"RES (MARTINEZ)_(TRAINING)TAPE.DOC.
.SKIP 1
\\
.LEFT MARGIN 7
^THE TRANSLATION TABLE IS AUTOMATICALLY CLEARED AFTER THE COMMAND
 USING IT HAS EXECUTED.
.SKIP 2
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.FILL.JUST
.INDEX <TITO <MODE <COMMAND
^^
.INDEX <TITO <MODE <COMMAND
.CENTER
THE MODE COMMAND
.CENTER
----------------
\\
.PARA
^THE <MODE COMMAND CONCERNS TWO DIFFERENT ASPECTS OF <TITO OPTIONS:
^THE FIRST SET OF OPTIONS PERTAINS TO WHAT <TITO SHOULD DO IF IT FINDS
A FILE WITH A NAME AND EXTENSION STRING ON DISK WHICH COULD BE OVERWRITTEN DURING
A <RESTORE OR <GET COMMAND BY A FILE ON TAPE WITH THE SAME FILENAME/EXTENSION;
^THE SECOND USE OF THE <MODE COMMAND DEALS WITH WHAT EXTENT OF INFORMATION
SHOULD BE OUTPUT BY <TITO DURING A <STORE OR <RESTORE OPERATION.
^THIS SECOND SET OF OPTIONS IS INVOLVED IN QUALITY ASSURANCE TECHNIQUES.
.PARA
^THE <MODE COMMAND HAS THREE PARTS. ^THE COMMAND PORTION IS ALWAYS <MODE.
^IF THIS COMMAND IS FOLLOWED BY ONLY A CARRIAGE RETURN, <TITO WILL TYPE
OUT THE CURRENT MODE SETTING.
^WHEN SPECIFYING OVERWRITE SETTING, THE SECOND PART OR OBJECT MAY BE EITHER
<OLD OR <SYS. ^THE OBJECT <OLD INDICATES ALL FILES EXCEPT THOSE IN DIRECTORY
(<SYS) WHICH EXIST ON BOTH DISC  AND  TAPE, WITH THE DISC FILE ABOUT TO BE
OVERWRITTEN  BY  A  <RESTORE OR <GET OPERATION. ^AN OBJECT OF <SYS
INDICATES FILES IN USERNAME <(SYS)  WHICH  ARE  VERY  CRITICAL  TO  THE
OPERATING SYSTEM AND THUS HAVE A SEPARATE <MODE STRING TO
PROTECT THEM AGAINST BEING OVERWRITTEN UNINTENTIONALLY.
.PARA
^THE THIRD PART OF
THIS COMMAND STRING, THE MODIFIER, INDICATES WHICH COPY OF THE FILE
TO KEEP SHOULD THE FILE ABOUT TO BE RESTORED EXIST ON BOTH TAPE AND DISC.
^OPTIONS AT THIS POINT ARE <NEWEST, <DISC, <TAPE, AND <CONFIRM.
.SKIP 1
.LEFT MARGIN 10
<NEWEST SELECTS THE MOST RECENT FILE, AS  DETERMINED  BY
THE CREATION DATE OF THE TAPE AND DISC FILES.
.SKIP 1
<DISC KEEPS THE DISC VERSION OF  THE  FILE.   <TITO  WILL
TYPEOUT THE MESSAGE "<NOT <WRITING <OVER <FILE ...".
.SKIP 1
<TAPE REPLACES THE DISC VERSION WITH  THE  TAPE VERSION  IN  ALL
CASES.
.SKIP 1
<CONFIRM IS  THE  DEFAULT  MODE  AND  REQUIRES  THAT  THE
OPERATOR CONFIRM BEFORE ANY DISC FILE IS OVERWRITTEN BY A TAPE FILE.
.LEFT MARGIN 7
.PARA
^REGARDING THE OTHER SET OF <MODE OPTIONS CONCERNING <TITO TYPEOUT,
THE SECOND PART OF THE
COMMAND STRING MAY BE EITHER <STORE OR <RESTORE. ^IN THIS CASE, THE MODIFIER
WILL BE USED TO SPECIFY WHAT IS TO BE PRINTED ON THE
OPERATOR'S  TERMINAL  DURING  THE  OPERATION.  ^THE  LISTING
OPTIONS ARE <TOTALS, <USERS, OR <FILES.
.SKIP 1
.LEFT MARGIN 10
<TOTALS PRINTS ONLY THE GRAND TOTALS FOR THE  OPERATION,
E.G. "<NNN <FILES <PROCESSED."
.SKIP 1
<USERS PRINTS TOTALS FOR  EACH  USER  ALONG  WITH  GRAND
TOTALS. ^THIS IS THE DEFAULT MODE.
.SKIP 1
<FILES  PRINTS  EACH  FILENAME  AS  IT  IS  READ/WRITTEN
FROM OR TO TAPE ALONG WITH THE USER TOTALS AND THE GRAND TOTAL. ^THIS SHOULD
BE USED DURING BATCH RESTORE AND STORE JOBS.
.SKIP 1
.LM 7
