.INDEX <TITO <DIRECTORY <COMMAND
^^
.CENTER
THE DIRECTORY COMMAND
.CENTER
---------------------
\\
.PARA
<TITO FEATURES AN EXPANDED TAPE DIRECTORY WHICH IS 86 COLUMNS
WIDE. ^IN  ADDITION,  EACH  SAVESET  HEADER RECORD PRINTOUT
INCLUDES THE SYSTEM IDENTIFICATION, THE  TAPE  DEVICE NUMBER,  
AND THE DENSITY AND NUMBER OF TRACKS RECORDED.
.SKIP 1
^THE DIRECTORY OUTPUT FORMAT IS GIVEN BELOW.
.NOFILL.NOJUST
^^
.SKIP 1
          COLUMNS         CONTENTS
          -------         --------
.SKIP 1
           00-05          FILE POSITION NO. IN OCTAL
.SKIP 1
           06-08          TAPE NO. IN SAVESET (1,2,3,...)
.SKIP 1
           12-17          FILENAME
.SKIP 1
           19-21          FILENAME EXTENSION
.SKIP 1
           27-38          USERNAME
.SKIP 1
           41-45          CREATION TIME
.SKIP 1
           47-55          CREATION DATE
.SKIP 1
           58-62          TIME TAPE WRITTEN
.SKIP 1
           64-72          DATE TAPE WRITTEN
.SKIP 1
           73-77          ALLOCATED SIZE OF FILE IN PAGES
.SKIP 1
           79-84          CHECKSUM
.FILL.JUST
\\
.PARA
^COLUMN HEADINGS ARE PRINTED FOR EACH USER, AND THE  <PPN  FOR
THE  USER IS PRINTED IN THE SAME LINE AS TOTAL USER FILES IN
COLUMNS 41-55. ^TOTAL PAGES ALLOCATED TO A USER IS  PRINTED
IN COLUMNS 72-77 OF THE SAME LINE.
.SKIP 15
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.FILL.JUST
^^
.INDEX <TITO <CUT <AFTER <COMMAND
.CENTER
THE CUT AFTER COMMAND
.CENTER
---------------------
\\
.PARA
^THE <CUT <AFTER COMMAND TAKES THE FOUT <AFTER <FILENAME AND
CAN  BE  USED  TO REDEFINE LOGICAL ^END ^OF ^TAPE (<EOT).
^IT POSITIONS THE TAPE OUT AFTER
THE SPECIFIED FILENAME AND WRITES A  DUMMY  SAVESET  TRAILER
RECORD  AND  TWO  FILEMARKS. ^THE  TAPE  IS THEN POSITIONED
BETWEEN THE TWO FILEMARKS WITH THE LOGICAL <EOT FLAG
SET,  SO  THAT  AN <APPEND AT THIS POINT INITIALIZES THE TAPE
FOR WRITING WITHOUT MOVING THE TAPE.
.PARA
^SINCE <CUT <AFTER IS A VERY DANGEROUS COMMAND, THE FOLLOWING APPROACH
SHOULD BE UNDERSTOOD TO AVOID LOSING TAPE FILES DUE TO
POSITIONING ERRORS.
.SKIP 1
^^
.INDEX <TITO <BACKUP <AND <A/F <TAPES
.CENTER;BACKUP AND ALL-FILE TAPES
.CENTER;-------------------------
\\
.PARA
^DON'T USE THE <"CUT <AFTER" COMMAND TO FIX AN ABORTED <"BACKUP"
OR <"ALL-FILE" TAPE.  ^RUN A FULL DIRECTORY TO THE LINE PRINTER;
DETERMINE THE LAST <"GOOD" TAPE POSITION; AND, WRITE THE INFORMATION
ABOUT THE LAST GOOD TAPE POSITION ON THE DIRECTORY.
^USE ANOTHER TAPE TO RESTART THE <"BACKUP" OR <"ALL-FILE", STARTING
WITH THE LAST FULL USER STORED BEFORE THE PREVIOUS TAPE ABORTED.
^^
.SKIP 1
.INDEX <TITO <CUSTOMER <TAPES
.CENTER;CUSTOMER TAPES
.CENTER;--------------
\\
.PARA
^WHEN A CUSTOMER TAPE ABORTS AND DOESN'T HAVE A LOGICAL <"EOT"
IT IS NECESSARY TO USE THE <"CUT <AFTER" COMMAND.  ^FIRST, RUN A FULL
DIRECTORY OF THE TAPE TO THE LINE PRINTER AND DETERMINE THE LAST <"GOOD"
TAPE POSITION.  ^DON'T USE THE <"WHERE" COMMAND TO DETERMINE CORRECT
TAPE POSITION (IT IS <UNTRUSTWORTHY).  ^BEFORE USING THE <"CUT <AFTER"
COMMAND, MAKE SURE THE TAPE IS REWOUND USING "<RWNW" AND THEN
ISSUE THE <"CUT <AFTER" COMMAND.  ^BE VERY CAREFUL THAT THE CORRECT
FILE NAME AND TAPE POSITION ARE CORRECT BEFORE CONFIRMING THE <"CUT
<AFTER" COMMAND.  (^REFER TO <"CONTINUING <ON <MULTIPLE <TAPES"
PARAGRAPH).
.PARA
^THERE MAY BE A NOTICEABLE DELAY BETWEEN THE TIME THE COMMAND
IS  GIVEN  AND  THE  TIME THE PROGRAM ASKS FOR THE TAPE POS.
RANGE. ^THE DELAY IS THE TIME IT TAKES <TITO TO LOCATE A FILE
HEADER RECORD ON TAPE.
.NOTE
^SEE <RESTARTING <ALLFILES <AND <DAILY <BACKUPS SECTION FOR EXAMPLES.
.END NOTE
.SKIP 6
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
