.INDEX <TITO <INDIRECT <FILES
.LM 7
USE OF INDIRECT FILES
----------------------
.LM 0
.SKIP 1
           THE FOLLOWING ARE EQUIVALENT:
.SKIP 1
          "*"STO (YOUNGERC)*.CMD STA W (YOUNGERC)USR.CMD_<12341,,456453>(CR)
.SKIP 1
          (OR)
.SKIP 1
          "*"STO @FOO STA W (YOUNGERC)USR.CMD_<12341,,456453>(CR)
.SKIP 1
          (WHERE FILE FOO. CONTAINS THE FOLLOWING LINE:)
           (YOUNGERC)*.CMD.
.SKIP 1
          (OR)
.SKIP 1
          "*"STO @FOO1 (YOUNGERC)USR.CMD_<10>_<12341,,456453>(CR)
.SKIP 1
          WHERE FILE FOO1. CONTAINS THE LINE:  (YOUNGERC)*.CMD STA 
.SKIP 1
          (OR)
.SKIP 1
          "*"STO @FOO2(CR)
.SKIP 1
          WHERE FILE FOO2. CONTAINS THE LINE:
          (YOUNGERC)*.CMD STA W (YOUNGERC)USR.CMD_<10>_<12341,,456453>
.SKIP 1
          MORE TYPICAL INDIRECT FILES MIGHT CONTAIN THE FOLLOWING:
          MULTIPLE USERNAMES, ONE ON EACH LINE OF THE INDIRECT FILE
.SKIP 1
          FOR EXAMPLE:
.SKIP 1
          (MARTINEZ)(CR)
          (TRAINING)(CR)
          (940MAN)(CR)
.SKIP 1
          OR MULTIPLE FILENAMES WITH THE FIRST ENTRY CONTAINING THE 
          USERNAME IN PARENTHESIS AND ONE FILE ENTRY PER LINE.
.SKIP 1
          FOR EXAMPLE:
.SKIP 1
          (HOLD)PILOT.SAV(CR)
          RKFOR.SHR(CR)
          LOGINN.SHR(CR)
.SKIP 7
.LM 7
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
