.INDEX <TITO <WRITE <ERRORS
\\
.FILL.JUST
.CENTER
<WRITE <ERRORS
.CENTER
------------
.PARA
^IF <TITO FAILS TO STORE ACROSS TAPE BOUNDARIES, IT WILL PROVIDE AN
ERROR MESSAGE EXPLAINING WHY. ^THE <STORE JOB SHOULD BE RESTARTED
MANUALLY ON THE NEXT TAPE USING THE '<START <WITH <FILENAME' MODIFIER.
.PARA
^IN GENERAL, WHEN TAPE WRITE ERRORS OCCUR, YOU WILL BE ASKED IF YOU
WISH TO CONTINUE WITH THE JOB. ^IF THE ANSWER IS <NO, AN END OF
FILE MARK WILL BE WRITTEN AND <TITO WILL RETURN TO COMMAND LEVEL;
IF YOU ANSWER <YES, THE <EOF WILL BE WRITTEN AND THE FILE WILL BE
STORED ON TAPE AGAIN. ^THIS MEANS THAT THE FILE IN QUESTION
WILL APPEAR TWICE ON THE TAPE DIRECTORY, WITH THE FIRST COPY
SHOWING A BAD CHECKSUM. ^ON A DISK REBUILD THE LATTER COPY WILL BE
RESTORED ON TOP OF THE EARLIER BAD COPY BUT ON OTHER RESTORE JOBS
YOU SHOULD BE CAREFUL NOT TO RESTORE THE BAD COPY OF THE FILE FROM
THE TAPE (E.G. WITH THE <MODE <OLD <NEW OPTION).
.PARA
^WHETHER OR NOT YOU SHOULD ANSWER '<YES' TO CONTINUE AFTER WRITE
ERRORS OCCUR DEPENDS ON WHAT KIND OF TAPE IS BEING WRITTEN:
.PARA
^IF THE TAPE IS A CUSTOMER TAPE:
ANSWER '<NO' AND REWIND THE TAPE. ^TRY CLEANING THE TAPE DRIVE. ^YOU 
MIGHT TRY REMOVING THE WRITE RING (THIS IS VERY IMPORTANT!) AND 
CLEANING THE TAPE. ^NEXT RUN A DIRECTORY OF THE LAST FEW
POSITIONS ON THE TAPE TO VERIFY THE CONDITION OF THE TAPE. ^IT IS
IMPORTANT TO NOTIFY YOUR LEAD OPERATOR OR SHIFT MANAGER IF YOU HAVE
A VERIFIED PROBLEM WITH A CUSTOMER TAPE. ^THEN IT  IS A GOOD IDEA
TO USE THE 'GET' COMMAND TO COPY THE LAST GOOD FILE THEN TRY TO
REDO THE STORE AGAIN USING THE CUT COMMAND IF APPROPRIATE. ^IF THIS
FAILS FOR SOME REASON YOU STILL HAVE A GOOD COPY OF THE FILE. ^IF YOU
CANNOT STORE THE FILES WITHOUT GETTING WRITE ERRORS IT IS NECESSARY
TO REBUILD THE TAPE. ^REMEMBER TO REMOVE THE WRITE RING FROM THE
ORIGINAL TAPE BEFORE YOU START. ^A TAPE REBUILD USUALLY INVOLVES RESTORING
ALL POSSIBLE FILES FROM THE TAPE TO A HOLDING DIRECTORY THEN STORING THE
FILES BACK OUT TO A NEW TAPE. ^DO NOT RETURN THE BAD TAPE TO THE TAPE
LIBRARY IF YOU HAVE ENCOUNTERED UNRECOVERABLE WRITE ERRORS. ^INSTEAD, 
NOFIFY YOUR SUPERVISOR OF WHAT WAS DONE. ^YOU SHOULD
PROVIDE THEM WITH THE ORIGINAL BAD TAPE.
.PARA
^IF THE TAPE IS A BACKUP OR ALL FILES TAPE:
^ANSWER <NO WHEN <TITO ASKS IF YOU WANT TO CONTINUE AFTER WRITE ERRORS.
^CLEAN THE TAPE DRIVE AND POSSIBLY THE TAPE (WRITE RING OUT FOR THIS).
^IF THE HARD WRITE ERRORS CONTINUE AFTER DOING THE ABOVE, ANSWER <NO
A SECOND TIME AND GET A NEW TAPE BEFORE CONTINUING FROM WHERE
THE STORE LEFT OFF. ^IT IS NOT NECESSARY TO REBUILD AN ALL FILES OR
BACKUP TAPE BUT IT SHOULD BE MARKED CLEARLY AS A BAD TAPE AND REMOVED
FROM THE SET FOR RECYCLE. ^LEAVE IT IN THE TAPE LIBRARY SO IT CAN BE
EVALUATED ON THE TAPE CLEANING MACHINE.
.PARA
^IF THE TAPE IS A SCRATCH TAPE BEING USED TO TRANSFER FILES:
ANSWER <YES AND CONTINUE WITH THE STORE. ^THE BAD FILE WILL BE REWRITTEN
BUT WHEN THE JOB IS ALL DONE, SEND THE SUSPECTED BAD TAPE TO THE
EVALUATOR.
.SUBTITLE <SAVING <A <FILE <STRUCTURE
