.INDEX <ASP <ERRORS/RECOVERIES
.LM 7
^&<ERRORS <AND <RECOVERIES\&
\\
.FILL.JUST
.PARA
<A.  <OUTPUT <ERROR <RECOVERY.  ^IF A WRITE ERROR IS ENCOUNTERED, A SECTION
OF BLANK TAPE ENOUGH TO COVER THE SIZE OF THE FAILED RECORD IS
WRITTEN ONTO THE TAPE AND THE RECORD IS RE-WRITTEN.  ^IF THE RETRY IS 
UNSUCCESSFUL, THEN ANOTHER SECTION OF BLANK TAPE IS WRITTEN, AND THE RECORD
IS TRIED ONCE AGAIN.  ^IF THIS CYCLE FINALLY SUCCEEDS IN SUCCESSFULLY WRITING
THE RECORD BEFORE <OECMAX TRIES (CURRENTLY 20 TRIES IS THE DEFAULT) THEN THE
<SAVE WILL PROCEED NORMALLY.  ^OTHERWISE, THE <OPERATOR IS ASKED TO SET THE
TAPE ASIDE AND MOUNT A NEW TAPE, AT WHICH POINT THE <SAVE IS RESTARTED
FROM THERE.  ^THE ONLY PROBLEM WITH THIS IS - 30 PAGES ARE LOST AND
THERE'S A GOOD CHANCE THE TAPE WON'T VERIFY.  ^IF A LOT OF <"DATA
<WRITE <ERRORS" OUTPUT, AND THE RECOVERY WAS <"UNSUCCESSFUL", ABORT THE JOB
AND START OVER WITH A "NEW" TAPE.
.PARA
^THE HEADER RECORD FOR EACH TAPE IS ACTUALLY READ BACK AFTER IT IS WRITTEN
TO ENSURE THAT IT MADE IT OUT TO THE TAPE SUCCESSFULLY.
.PARA
<B.  <INPUT <ERROR <RECOVERY.  ^ON INPUT, IF AN <I/O ERROR OR CONSISTENCY 
ERROR (BAD RECORD SEQUENCE NUMBER, BAD PROLOGUE CODE) IS ENCOUNTERED, THE TAPE
IS SEARCHED BACKWARDS FOR THE LAST GOOD RECORD.  ^IF IT IS NOT
FOUND, THE TAPE IS SEARCHED FORWARDS FOR THE FIRST GOOD RECORD THAT CAN BE
FOUND.  ^IF IT IS FOUND, A MESSAGE STATING WHAT THE LAST DISK PAGE RESTORED
OR VERIFIED IS PRINTED.  ^THE TAPE IS THEN SEARCHED FOR THE NEXT GOOD RECORD.
^IF IT IS NOT FOUND ON THE REMAINDER OF THE TAPE, THE <OPERATOR IS ASKED TO
MOUNT THE NEXT TAPE (IF ONE EXISTS).  ^OTHERWISE, THE RESTORE CONTINUES FROM
THE RECORD THAT WAS FOUND.
.PARA
<C.  <FATAL <TAPE <OUTPUT <ERRORS.  ^TAPE SHOULD BE GIVEN TO ^TAPE ^LIBRARIAN
FOR SALVAGE OR FOR SCRAPPING.  ^ANOTHER TAPE SHOULD BE MADE TO TAKE ITS PLACE
IN THE SET.
.PARA
<D.  <TAPE <OVERWRITES.  <ASP WILL NOT ALLOW A TAPE TO BE OVERWRITTEN
DURING A GIVEN <ASP <SAVE <RUN IF THE <HEADER ON THAT TAPE INDICATES THAT
IT HAS BEEN WRITTEN DURING THE RUN.  ^SHOULD THE OCCASION ARISE, AN <ERROR
MESSAGE WILL OUTPUT.
\\
.PARA
<E.  <OECMAX <AND <SRCLEN <COMMANDS.  ^THESE COMMANDS SET THE NUMBER OF
TIMES AN OUTPUT RECORD IS TRIED TO BE WRITTEN OUT BEFORE ASKING FOR A 
NEW TAPE, AND THE NUMBER OF RECORDS TO BE SEARCH IN INPUT ERROR RECOVERY
FOR A GOOD RECORD IN THE FORWARD DIRECTION.  <UNDER <NORMAL <CIRCUMSTANCES,
<THESE <COMMANDS <SHOULD <NOT <BE <USED.
