.LEFT MARGIN 7
.AUTOPARAGRAPH
.CENTER
MAGCON - MAGNETIC TAPE CONVERSION
.CENTER
------ - -------- ---- ----------
.INDEX <MAGCON <INTRODUCTION
.SKIP 1
I.  INTRODUCTION TO MAGCON
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
MAGCON is a program which transfers data and will convert
from one character set to another in the process.  It runs
on the TYMCOM X and is designed mainly for use with magnetic
tapes and disk (FTA, MTA and DSK) although it will
use other devices.  MAGCON will perform blocking, duplication,
character set conversion, unblocking, and positioning.  It can
also prepare an octal dump of a file which can be
printed or type a file containing text.
.SKIP 1
MAGCON may be used in either of two modes, dialog or
command.  During dialog mode, information is input to MAGCON
in terms of answers to questions.  Command mode requires the
user to input in a specific format the information needed to
effect a data transfer or store a command or perform other
functions.  MAGCON can be operated from command files.  When
MAGCON is started up, it is in dialog mode; to change to
command mode, an "!" is input as the answer to the first
question.  (See Sections 3 and 4.)
.SKIP 1
Character sets with more than 128 characters cannot be fully
handled, and characters in some sets may not have
suitable equivalents in the target desired sets.  ^If a character
cannot be translated, MAGCON places a back slash "_\" in that
position in the record.  A tally of the number of bad
characters (not translatable) is printed out when the
transfer is complete.
.SKIP 1
In general, commands and switches may be abbreviated to
any number of characters that will allow that command to
be uniquely interpreted.  However, no more than six characters
are checked for validity in any of the commands.
.SKIP 1
A command file that MAGCON will read for commands is denoted
by the character "@".
.SKIP 1
To leave MAGCON, type an <alt-mode or a <control <c (_^<c) or use the
QUIT command during command mode.
.SKIP 10
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.FILL.JUST
.INDEX <MAGCON <DEFINITIONS
II.  Definitions
.SKIP 1
The following definitions should be helpful in understanding
the information that must be supplied to MAGCON.
.SKIP 1
BLOCK
.SKIP 1
A block pertains to a set of one or more records which
MAGCON deals with as a unit.  On a tape, this will be
the same as a physical record.
.SKIP 1
LOGICAL RECORD
.SKIP 1
A record refers to a contiguous set of characters which
may be delimited by a CR-LF sequence or be defined by a
character count.  A record is artificially defined; it
has no relationship to the device.
.SKIP 1
BLOCK FACTOR
.SKIP 1
This refers to the number of records contained in a block.  This
is a value that the user of MAGCON must supply for
tape files.  Blocking, the grouping of records together in
a block involves a special structure or meaning in only
two cases.  One is the special block structure of a VEBCDIC
file, and the other is the separation of HPASCII blocks with
blank tape.  (See also Section 5.)
.SKIP 1
UNBLOCKED TAPE
.SKIP 1
In this context, an unblocked tape will refer to one whose
block factor is one.
.SKIP 1
PHYSICAL RECORD
.SKIP 1
A physical record is device dependent and refers to the
smallest unit of data that can be processed by the hardware
(128 words for disk, 80 columns for card reader, the data
between gaps for magnetic tape).  The blocks and records
mentioned above may cross the boundaries of these
physical records.
.SKIP 1
CHARACTER OR BYTE
.SKIP 1
The number of bits forming a character or byte is dependent
on the mode of the data.  If one is reading an EBCDIC tape,
the character size of the input is considered to be eight
bits.  If operating in image mode, the byte size dealt with
is a whole word, 36 bits.
.SKIP 1
INDUSTRY TAPE
.SKIP 1
An industry tape or industry compatible tape refers to
one whose character size is eight bits and which can be read or
written four characters at a time (in 32 bit words).
.SKIP 4
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
EOF MARK
.FILL.JUST
.SKIP 1
An EOF mark follows every file on a magnetic tape.  It consists
of a record containing an octal 17 (for 7-track tapes) or an
octal 23 (for 9-track tapes).
.SKIP 1
EOT MARK
.SKIP 1
MAGCON does not write any special end of tape mark.
.SKIP 40
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.FILL.JUST
.INDEX <MAGCON <DIALOG <DESCRIPTION
III.  Questions Asked in Dialog Mode
.SKIP 1
A set of questions is asked the user for the input and output
files.  The first two questions are always asked.  Depending
upon the answers to those questions and whether the file is
for input or output, the remaining questions which apply
will be asked.  Changes to the numbered questions, asked during the
dialog or not, may be made as noted when MAGCON prompts for
corrections following the dialog, or before a repeat.
.SKIP 1
1. FILE:
.SKIP 1
Enter a file name which may take one of the following general
forms.
.SKIP 1
.CENTER;DEVICE:FILE.EXTENSION(username)
.SKIP 1
.CENTER;or
.SKIP 1
.CENTER;DEVICE:(username)FILE.EXT
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
The complete file specification is optional and will take on
default values if any part of it is omitted.  For example,
the device will default to DSK: and the user name to the current
disk area.  The input and output file names will be
created as follows.  The file names will have the form
FILXXX where XXX is a three-digit number, and the file extensions
will have the form XXX where is XXX is the same three-digit
number.  Numbering starts at 001 when MAGCON is run, and the
values are incremented as needed to get unique file names.
.SKIP 1
If the output device is a magnetic tape, and the drive is
write-locked, MAGCON allows the user to remount the
tape correctly and continue.  MAGCON will type:
.NOFILL.NOJUST
.SKIP 1
        FILE "file spec." STRUCTURE IS WRITE-LOCKED.
        REMOUNT TAPE IF YOU WISH TO CONTINUE
        CONTINUE?
.FILL.JUST
.SKIP 1
A "<YES" answer tells MAGCON to continue.  A "<NO"
answer causes the program to restart the output dialog.
.SKIP 15
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.FILL.JUST
Changes:  There are no restrictions; however the rest of the
dialog for either input or output is done over if
the device changes from the previous value.
.SKIP 1
Wild card file names (or parts of names) may be used to effect
various transfers of multiple files.  The following table
explains results of the legal wild card transfers.
.SKIP 1
.INDEX <MAGCON <DEVICE <ALTERNATIVES
.NOFILL.NOJUST
INPUT           OUTPUT          RESULT
-----           ------          ------
.SKIP 1
FTAn:*.*        file name       Reads all tape files
MTAn:*.*                        to one disk file.
.SKIP 1
FTAn:*.*        *.*             Reads all tape files to
MTAn:*.*                        separate disk files
                                with unique names
                                created by MAGCON.
.SKIP 1
FTAn:*.*        name.*          Reads all tape files to
MTAn:*.*                        separate disk files
                                with names of the form
                                name.XXX where XXX is a
                                three-digit number.
.SKIP 1
FTAn:*.*        *.ext           Reads all tape files to
MTAn:*.*                        separate disk files
                                with names of the form
                                FILXXX.ext where XXX is
                                a three-digit number.
.SKIP 1
standard        FTAn:           Transfers appropriate
wild card       MTAn:           disk files to one tape
notation                           file.
("_#" AND "*")
.SKIP 1
standard        FTAn:*.*        Transfers appropriate
wild card       MTAn:*.*        disk files to separate
notation                           file.
("_#" AND "*")
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
WARNING:##When using wild card transfers, it is important
to replace the file name when repeating specifications, even if
the same transfer is desired, since the wild card names are
replaced by real names as MAGCON is running.
.SKIP 1
