3. VARIABLE LENGTH RECORDS?
.SKIP 1
This question is asked for disk and mag tape devices
if the specified mode is ASCII, HPASCII,
or GEASCII.  The supplied default is <YES for VEBCDIC and SIXBIT
mode and <NO otherwise.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  no restrictions.
.SKIP 1
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
4. CRLF'S IN ASCII FILE?
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
Are  carriage-return  line-feed  sequences  included  in   ASCII,
HPASCII and GEASCII files?  This question applies only to
one of these three types of files on a disk or mag tape
and is not asked otherwise.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  The value may be changed if mode is HPASCII, GEASCII,
or ASCII.
.SKIP 1
5[A]. [MAXIMUM] RECORD SIZE
.SKIP 1
One form of this question is always asked if disk or mag tape
device and not in OCTAL mode.  The bracketed
portion is printed for variable length record files.  Enter the number of
characters in a logical record or, for variable length records, the
maximum number.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Need same conditions as for question to be
asked.  When making a change, the
item number to enter is "5" and never "5A" regardless of
which form of the question was asked.
.SKIP 1
6. BLOCKING FACTOR:
.SKIP 1
This question is asked for non-disk files.  Enter
the number of logical
records contained in one block.  The supplied default is
1 for tapes and 0 for disk (to satisfy MAGCON) when the question
is not asked or when the user supplies a 0.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Can be changed if tape.
.SKIP 1
8. STOP ON ERRORS?
.SKIP 1
This question is always asked.  Should the job be aborted on
a parity error in the file in question?
.SKIP 1
Changes:  no restrictions.
.SKIP 1
9. HEADERS FOR LPT?
.SKIP 1
Should the LPT (line printer)
listing include a header consisting of the  user's
user name, output file name, extension, time and date?
.SKIP 1
Changes: Can be changed if LPT device.
.SKIP 1
NOTE:  Questions numbered 10 through 20 are asked for
tape files only.
.SKIP 6
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.FILL.JUST
10. IS THIS AN ULTRA TECH TAPE?
.SKIP 1
This question is not normally asked, and the supplied default
is <NO.  This feature supplies a
terminator (octal 25) for each logical record in the non-ASCII
output file.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Changes may be made if the following conditions
are all true.  The file must be output, tape, and in any mode
other than one of the three ASCII modes.  The input file
must currently be in ASCII.
.SKIP 1
11. DENSITY:
.SKIP 1
What is the density of the magnetic tape?  The options are:
.NOFILL.NOJUST
.SKIP 1
          200
          556
          800
          1600
          6250
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Changeable for tape devices.
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
12. PARITY:
.SKIP 1
This question is asked for 7-track tapes only.  The supplied default
is ODD otherwise.  Enter the parity of the magnetic tape,
ODD or EVEN.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Value may be changed if device is a 7-track tape.
.SKIP 1
13. ADVANCE:
.SKIP 1
Enter the number of eof marks that MAGCON should advance before
processing  a  file.   If  a  magnetic  tape  has labels, there may be
several eof marks per file, depending on the label type.  If there  is
no advance count, the user should input a zero.
.SKIP 1
.NOFILL.NOJUST
    BACKSPACE:
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
Tells MAGCON to backspace the magnetic tape n eof marks and  then
forword  space  one  eof  mark  if  the  tape  is  not  at load point.
BACKSPACE is asked only if the answer to ADVANCE was zero.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Changeable for tapes.
.SKIP 1
14. ADVANCE RECORDS:
.SKIP 1
This question is asked for input tape files.  The
supplied default is 0.  Enter the number of logical records to skip
before reading the tape file.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Changeable for tapes.
.SKIP 1
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
15. REWIND:
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
When should the magnetic tape be rewound?  The options are:
.SKIP 1
.NOFILL.NOJUST
          BEFORE (the operation)
          AFTER (the operation)
          ALWAYS (before and after the operation)
          OMIT (do not rewind)
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Changeable for tapes.
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
NOTE:  The following feature is not fully operational (at least not
for IBM labels).  In order to read back a labeled tape, the
advance records or advance files options may be used to skip
over extra records or file marks.
.SKIP 1
16. LABEL:
.SKIP 1
What should the label look like?  The options are:
.SKIP 1
.NOFILL.NOJUST
          NONE (no label)
          MINE (special DEC labels)
          DIGITAL   (DEC COBOL labels)
          BURROUGHS (standard BURROUGHS labels)
          IBM (IBM 360 labels)
          GE635 (General Electric 635 labels)
.FILL.JUST
.SKIP 1
Labels are written in the character set specified except for  IBM  and
GE635  labels.   IBM  labels are written in BCD for 7-track drives and
EBCDIC for 9-track drives.  GE635 labels are always written in GEBCD.
.SKIP 1
If a label is used, the following 2 questions are asked:
.SKIP 1
    REEL:
.SKIP 1
Sets the reel serial number in labels  that  have  this  feature.
For some labels the reel serial number is retained when writing over a
label.  For instance, for BURROUGHS labels the output tape is read  to
retrieve  the  serial number and then a new label is written with this
number.  To override this feature the reel option  is  given  and  the
output tape is not read first.
.SKIP 1
    SCAN TAPE FOR FILE?
.SKIP 1
Should the magnetic tape be searched until the input file name
is found or an end of tape condition is detected.  The search is in
a forward direction only.  (Used with labelled tapes only.)
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Changeable for tapes.
.NOFILL.NOJUST
.SKIP 1
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
18. SPECIAL 36-BIT MODE?
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
This question is not asked during the dialog and is defaulted to
NO.  It refers to a means of interpreting the characters read
in from tape as a series of 8-bit characters in a packed format
containing four and one-half characters per word (characters may
cross word boundaries.  (The author has found no case in which
MAGCON stores the characters read from tape in this fashion; it
may be an obsolete feature.)
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Changeable if tape and the mode is either HPASCII,
EBCDIC, or VEBCDIC.
.SKIP 40
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
19. INDUSTRY TAPE?
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
This question is not asked during the dialog.  The default is <YES for
EBCDIC and HPASCII tapes and <NO otherwise.  This refers to a
tape in industry compatible mode in which its 8-bit characters
are written or read in groups of four (a 32-bit word).  The
buffer storage of characters to be written (or just read)
contains words of four characters with the low order four bits
not used.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Changeable if tape and the mode is either HPASCII,
EBCDIC, or VEBCDIC.
.SKIP 1
20. UNLOAD TAPE?
.SKIP 1
Should the magnetic tape  be  unloaded  after  the  operation  is
completed?
.SKIP 1
Changes:  no restrictions.
.SKIP 1
22. MULTIPLE OUTPUT FILES FOR THIS INPUT FILE?
.SKIP 1
This question is asked for input files.  MAGCON will allow the
user to split up the input file by blocks into separate
output files.  In this case, a block is considered to be a
physical record on the particular device involved.  if
the user answers <YES, then the following
questions will be asked:
.SKIP 1
   NUMBER OF BLOCKS TO SKIP:
.SKIP 1
If the input file is being  split  into  separate  output  files,
MAGCON  allows the user to skip a number of blocks before writing into
the output file.
.SKIP 1
   NUMBER OF BLOCKS TO TRANSFER:
.SKIP 1
If the input file is being  split  into  separate  output  files,
MAGCON asks how many blocks to transfer.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Need same conditions as for question to be asked.
.SKIP 1
23. DO YOU WISH ONLY 1 OUTPUT RECORD PER INPUT RECORD?
.SKIP 1
This question is asked if output, the file is on disk, the
mode is either GEASCII, HPASCII, or ASCII, and the output
record size is less than the input record size.  In
other cases, the supplied default is <YES meaning the output
records may be truncated.  If the user answers <NO, then
MAGCON will create a new record from information remaining from
an input record which will not fit in the output record.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Need same conditions as for question to be asked.
.SKIP 1
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
24. DELETE TRAILING BLANKS?
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
This question is asked for output files when the device is
disk and the mode is HPASCII, GEASCII, or ASCII.  It does not
apply to other cases.
.SKIP 1
Changes:  Need same conditions as for question to be asked.
.SKIP 1
NOTE:  All of the above numbered questions may be changed as
noted when MAGCON requests corrections at the end of
dialog for input specifications and for output specifications.  For
example:
.NOFILL.NOJUST
.SKIP 1
ALL [INPUT ] ENTRIES CORRECT?
    [OUTPUT]
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
To change one of the attributes, enter "N" to this
question.  Then MAGCON will ask:
.SKIP 1
ITEM TO CHANGE?
.SKIP 1
Enter the number of the appropriate question.  MAGCON will ask
the question if the change conditions are met, and the answer
can be supplied.  These questions continue until
a "Y" answer indicates all entries are correct.  MAGCON allows
corrections after each dialog or before a repeat.  Enter input
changes only when MAGCON asks about input entries and output
entries only when MAGCON asks about output entries.
.SKIP 1
NOTE:  The remaining questions are not numbered and cannot
be altered once they are answered.
.SKIP 1
USING "DSK:MAGCON.DAT" CONVERSION FILE - OK?
.SKIP 1
This question is asked if MAGCON finds a conversion file in
the user's directory.  If it is acceptable to use this
file, then answer <YES.  If a <NO answer is given, then
the standard file found in SYS is used.  For more information
about using a special conversion table, see the documentation for
the program MAGTAB found in MAGTAB.DOC and also
MAGCON.INF.
.SKIP 1
SUBSTITUTIONS?
.SKIP 1
MAGCON allows the user to make a small number of changes to the
standard substitutions in the conversion table MAGCON uses by
entering them from the keyboard.  If this question is answered
affirmatively, MAGCON will type:
.SKIP 1
MAKE SUBSTITUTONS:
.SKIP 1
Type the new character first.  MAGCON will type " for  ".  Then
type the character to substituted for.  When done with all the
substitutions, type an extra carriage return.
.SKIP 3
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
EXAMPLE:
.SKIP 1
.NOFILL.NOJUST
SUBSTITUTIONS?  Y
A FOR Z
Z FOR A
                (extra carriage return)
.SKIP 1
.FILL.JUST
Each time MAGCON encounteres an "A" in the input file, a "Z" will be
substituted and vica-versa.  Printing characters are the only
characters that may be used for substituting.
.SKIP 1
OKAY TO WRITE ON OLD FILE?
.SKIP 1
Is it all right to write over the existing file on disk with
the name specified?
.SKIP 1
REPEAT SPECIFICATIONS?
.SKIP 1
This question is asked following a completed data transfer.  The
transfer may be repeated with the same specifications, or the
user may correct individual responses; MAGCON will ask if
all input and then all output specifications are correct.  If
either the file device or the mode changes, then the remaining questions
of the dialog will be asked.  In other cases, the user
will be responsible for changed responses which should be altered
to conform with any of his/her corrections.  Use with
care.  (See warning concerning the use of wild card file
names at the beginning of this section.)
.SKIP 25
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.FILL.JUST
.INDEX <MAGCON <COMMAND <MODE <DESCRIPTION
IV.  Command Mode Structure
.NOTE
THIS FORM OF MAGCON IS SELDOM USED; DESPITE IT'S ADVANTAGES, IT IS MORE
DIFFICULT FOR THE OPERATOR SINCE THE PROGRAM WILL DO NO PROMPTING
FOR INPUT AND OUTPUT SPECIFICATION.
.END NOTE
IV.A  Format of Data Transfer Commands
.SKIP 1
The commands which effect a data transfer, performing the
same function as the dialog, use the traditional DECsystem-10
command string format.  MAGCON will accept one input
file specification and one output file specification separated by
a back arrow "__" or equal sign "=".  For example:
.SKIP 1
.CENTER;OUTPUT FILE__INPUT FILE
.SKIP 1
.CENTER;or
.SKIP 1
.CENTER;OUTPUT FILE=INPUT FILE
.SKIP 1
The file specifications are the same as described in Section 2,
question 1 except that the device name must always be
present.
.SKIP 1
IV.B  Switches for Data Transfer Commands
.SKIP 1
Each input or output file file specification must contain
switches to give MAGCON the necessary information about the
files being handled.  A switch begins with a slash and is
terminated by the next slash or by the carriage return
which terminates the whole command as well.  For example:
.SKIP 1
.CENTER;/SWITCH
.SKIP 1
.CENTER;or
.SKIP 1
.CENTER;/SWITCH:ARGUMENT
.SKIP 1
In all cases, switches may be abbreviated to the number of
characters that will allow unique interpretation of that
switch.  In the following table of possible switches, "n" represents
an integer decimal number, and "ARG" represents a key word
that must be present.  The values of the switches and the
arguments should be apparent from referencing the
corresponding dialog question.  Switches flagged with an "*"
can be turned off or have the opposite effect noted by
concatenating "<NO" with the switch.  For example:  NOLIST,
NOCRLF.
.NOFILL.NOJUST
.SKIP 4
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
                DIALOG
SWITCH          Q. _#    EXPLANATION
------          ------  -----------
.SKIP 1
/ADVANCE:n      13      The number of file marks to skip.
.SKIP 1
/BACKSPACE:n    13      The number of file marks to backspace
                        over.
.SKIP 1
/BLOCK:n
/BLKSIZE:n       6      Blocking factor.
.SKIP 1
/CRLF *          4      CR-LF sequences in file.
.SKIP 1
/DELBLANKS *    24      Delete trailing blanks.
.SKIP 1
/DENSITY:ARG    11      Magnetic tape density.
.SKIP 1
/ERROR *         8      Stop on errors.
.SKIP 1
/FLIST                  Lists the input device's
                        directory for the selected
                        file or files (short form).
.SKIP 1
/HEADER *        9      Headers on LPT listing.
.SKIP 1
/INDUSTRY *     19      Industry compatible magnetic tape.
.SKIP 1
/LABEL:ARG      16      Labelled tape.
.SKIP 1
/LIST *                 Lists the input device's
                        directory for the selected
                        file or files (long form).
                        (NOLIST clears LIST or FLIST.)
.SKIP 1
/MODE:ARG        2      The character set mode of the file.
.SKIP 1
/PARITY:ARG     12      Magnetic tape parity.
.SKIP 1
/PASSWORD:ARG   16      Sets the password for GE365 labels to
                        the value of the argument (up to 12
                        characters).
.SKIP 1
/RECORD:n
/RECSIZE:n       5      The number of bytes in a record.
.SKIP 1
/REEL:ARG       16      Reel serial number in the label.
.SKIP 1
/RETAIN                 Saves the current command string for
                        later use or editing.  See the RETAIN
                        command for a complete description of
                        the retain function.
.SKIP 1
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
/REWIND:ARG *   15      When tape should be rewound.
.SKIP 1
/RUN                    Performs RETAIN command and then
                        executes the current command string.
                        See the RUN command for a complete
                        description.
.SKIP 1
/SCAN *         16      Search for file on labelled tape.
.SKIP 1
/SKIPRECORDS:n  14      How many records should be skipped?
.SKIP 1
/SPAN *          3      Variable or fixed length records.
.SKIP 1
/TELL *                 Specifies that MAGCON should type
                        out the file names as they are found
                        (default).
.SKIP 1
/UNLOAD *       20      Unload tape when transfer complete.
.NOFILL.NOJUST
