.SKIP 1
^THE HELPFUL HINTS DOCUMENTED BELOW ARE DERIVED FROM <MAGCON
EXPERIENCES AND ARE PRESENTED TO ASSIST YOU WITH SITUATIONS WHICH
MIGHT OTHERWISE BE UNDULY TROUBLESOME.
.SKIP 1
^WHEN DOING A <MAGCON RESTORE, YOU SHOULD ALWAYS WORK FROM A
<TYMCOM-X UTILITY DIRECTORY (E.G., <OPER). 
^ONLY AFTER THE CONVERSION HAS BEEN <QA'D SHOULD FILES BE RENAMED INTO
THE USER'S DIRECTORY.
.SKIP 1
^THE MOST COMMON DATA FORMATS IN USE TODAY ARE <ASCII, <HPASCII,
<EBCDIC AND <VEBCDIC.
<BCD IS SELDOM USED.
.SKIP 1
9-TRACK TAPES ALWAYS USE ODD PARITY.
.SKIP 1
7-TRACK TAPES USUALLY USE EVEN PARITY.
.SKIP 1
^THERE IS NO GUARANTEED <MAGCON CAPABILITY TO CONVERT BINARY FILES
EXCEPT TO OR FROM ANOTHER <PDP-10.
^THE <IMAGE OPTION ASSUMES THE CONVERSION WILL BE 36-BIT WORD TO
36-BIT WORD.
.SKIP 1
^GIVEN THE ABOVE LIMITAION, IF YOU SHOULD GET A <MAGCON JOB DESCRIPTION
TO CONVERT "ALL THE FILES IN MY DIRECTORY" INCLUDING 
<REL AND <SAV EXTENSION FILES, EXPECT THAT THOSE BINARY FILES
WON'T CONVERT PROPERLY.
^UNLESS THE DESTINATION COMPUTER HAS A FANCY CONVERSION PROGRAM
AT THE USER'S END, BINARY CONVERSIONS PROBABLY WON'T WORK.
.SKIP 1
^IF A <MAGCON REQUESTS THAT <HPASCII BE USED, IT IS VERY LIKELY
THE USER'S SYSTEM IS A MINI-COMPUTER; MOST MINI'S USE 8-BIT 
<ASCII, ESPECIALLY ON 16-BIT WORD LENGTHS WHERE 8-BIT CAN RESULT IN
TWO CHARACTERS PER WORD.
^THE <PDP-10'S, ON THE OTHER HAND, USE 7-BIT <ASCII.
.SKIP 1
^IF YOU RUN INTO TROUBLE IN A <PDP-10 CONVERSION, IT MIGHT BE
A GOOD IDEA TO SUGGEST THAT <PIP BE USED INSTEAD OF <MAGCON.
.SKIP 1
^ONE OF THE MAIN PROBLEMS IN <MAGCON IS WHEN THE USER DOESN'T
UNDERSTAND OR KNOW THE RECORD LENGTH INVOLVED IN THE JOB.
^TO HELP FIND OUT WHAT RECORD LENGTH APPLIES, IT IS VERY HELPFUL
TO FIND OUT WHAT TYPE OF COMPUTER THE <MAGCON IS TO BE USED FOR.
.SKIP 1
^IN GENERAL, IT IS BEST TO USE FIXED LENGTH RECORDS, ESPECIALLY
IF YOU CAN SUPPLY THE RECORD LENGTH OF THE LONGEST RECORD IN THE
FILE; THEN SMALLER RECORDS IN THE FILE WILL BE FILLED IN BY <MAGCON.
.SKIP 1
^HOWEVER, FOR MOST <ASCII OR <EBCDIC CONVERSIONS, THE ANSWER TO THE
PROMPT FOR "<VARIABLE <LENGTH <RECORDS?" SHOULD GENERALLY BE <YES.
.SKIP 1
^THE LAW OF DIMINISHING RETURNS CERTAINLY CAN APPLY TO
<MAGCON.
^YOU SHOULD NOT SPEND HOURS ON CONFUSING TAPE CONVERSION; IT IS
RECOMMENDED THAT YOU SPEND NO LONGER THAN 30-45 MINUTES TRYING TO
DISCOVER THE CORRECT <MAGCON SPECIFICATIONS.
.SKIP 3
.NOFILL.NOJUST
<BTNA ^TAPE ^PROCEDURES
^REVISION 2; 10/21/93
.PAGE
.FILL.JUST
^AFTER THAT A CALL TO THE CUSTOMER OR HIS/HER <BT <TYMNET <INC REPRESENTATIVE
FOR BETTER INFORMATION IS PROBABLY THE BEST COURSE OF
ACTION.
^REMEMBER, IT IS NOT UNUSUAL FOR A REQUESTED <MAGCON TO BE TECHNICALLY
IMPOSSIBLE TO PERFORM CORRECTLY.
.SKIP 1
.CENTER
<MAGCON <QA <HINTS
.SKIP 1
^USE THE <MAGCON TERMINAL HARDCOPY FOR THE DIRECTORY OF THE CONVERTED
TAPE; IT WILL SHOW THE TAPE POSITIONS.
.SKIP 1
^COMPARING <CHECKSUM'S IS NOT A GOOD WAY TO <QA A <MAGCON; EVEN IF THE
CONVERSION WAS CORRECT, THERE WERE PROBABLY ENOUGH VARIABLES INVOLVED
IN THE CONVERSION SO THAT THE CONVERTED FILE'S <CHECKSUM WILL NOT AGREE 
WITH THE ORIGINAL FILE'S <CHECKSUM.
.SKIP 1
^IF <MAGCON REPORTS "BAD CHARACTERS", THIS DOES NOT REFLECT <READ
OR <WRITE ERRORS.
^RATHER, IT MEANS THAT IT WAS UNABLE TO TRANSLATE CERTAIN CHARACTERS
FROM ONE MODE TO ANOTHER.
^THIS IS TO BE EXPECTED IN SOME MODES; CERTAIN <EBCDIC CHARACTERS MIGHT 
NOT BE IN THE <PDP-10 CONVERSION TABLES.
^IT IS THE NUMBER OF "BAD CHARACTERS" WHICH IS CRUCIAL.
^ALL BAD CHARACTERS WILL HAVE A BACKSLASH IN PLACE OF THE 
UNTRANSLATABLE CHARACTER.
^CHECK THE LISTING OF THE CONVERTED FILE; IF THERE IS A HIGH NUMBER OF
BACKSLASHES, A CALL TO THE CUSTOMER OR HIS/HER <BT <TYMNET <INC REPRESENTATIVE
MIGHT BE IN ORDER.
.SKIP 1
^MOST OF THE DATA INVOLVED IN <MAGCONS IS IN FIELD FORMAT--THAT 
IS, COLUMNS.
^IF THE LISTING YOU OUTPUT DOESN'T LINE UP, THERE ARE TWO 
COMMON REASONS:
.SKIP 1
.INDENT5
1. ^SLANTING COLUMNS INDICATE THAT THE RECORD LENGTH NUMBER
YOU INPUT MIGHT BE OFF A FEW CHARACTERS.
.SKIP 1
.INDENT5
2. ^WHEN THE DATA APPEARS TO WRAP AROUND THE LISTING, THERE 
MAY BE AN INCORRECT BLOCKING FACTOR INPUT.
.SKIP 1
^IF <MAGCON PRINTOUT SHOWS ONE LONG LINE WITH *** IN EACH RIGHTHAND
MARGIN, IT MAY BE CORRECTED BY ANSWERING <NO TO THE QUESTION:
^^
"<CR <LF <IN <DATA?"
\\
^NORMALLY, AND ESPECIALLY FOR <ASCII DATA, THE ANSWER TO THIS
QUESTION SHOULD BE <YES.
.SKIP 15
.NOFILL.NOJUST
