.INDEX <PIP <INTRODUCTION
((<INTRODUCTION))
.FILL.JUST
.PARAGRAPH
<PIP IS THE SUBSYSTEM PROVIDED BY ^DIGITAL ^EQUIPMENT ^CORP TO
PROVIDE FOR THE TRANSFER OF FILES ON THE <PDP-10 FROM ANY STANDARD
INPUT/OUTPUT DEVICE TO ANY OTHER STANDARD INPUT/OUTPUT DEVICE.
.PARAGRAPH
^THROUGH USE OF VARIOUS SWITCHES, <PIP CAN PERFORM SIMPLE EDITING OF
THE FILES AS THEY ARE TRANSFERRED FROM ONE DEVICE TO ANOTHER.
^IT CAN ALSO CONTROL CERTAIN MAGNETIC TAPE CONTROL FUNCTIONS AS
SETTING DENSITY, PARITY, AND POSITIONING THE TAPE.
^THE PROGRAM REFERENCES <MTA'\\S (OLDER <DEC DRIVES)
AND <FTA'\\S (NEWER <STC DRIVES).
^USERNAMES ON THE <TYMCOM-X MUST BE CONVERTED TO <PPN'S
(<PROJECT-PROGRAMMER <NUMBERS) IF THEY ARE TO BE USED AS AN OPERAND
OF A <PIP COMMAND.
.NOTE
^IN THE EXEC, A LEGAL USERNAME CAN BE CONVERTED INTO IT'S <PPN
BY USING THE COMMAND
^^
PPN USERNAME (CR).
\\
^FOR ADDITIONAL DETAILS, REFER TO THE MINI-MANUAL TITLED
<TYMCOM-X <ACCOUNTING <AND <USERS.
^FOR A THOROUGH DOCUMENTATION ON ALL ASPECTS OF <PIP YOU ARE
REFERRED TO THE <DEC-10-PPEO-D WRITEUP ON <PIP (CONTAINED IN
<DECSYSTEM-10 <USER'S <HANDBOOK <AND <REFERENCE <MANUAL).
.END NOTE
.INDEX <PIP <COMMAND <SUMMARY
((<COMMAND <SUMMARY))
.PARAGRAPH
<PIP IS ACCESSED FROM THE <EXEC BY TYPING '.^R <PIP(CR)'
AND RESPONDS WITH AN ASTERISK (*) TO INDICATE THAT IT IS
READY FOR COMMANDS.
^THE COMMAND STRING IS ENTERED TO PERFORM THE DESIRED OPERATION AND
THE STRING IS TERMINATED AND EXECUTED WHEN A CARRIAGE RETURN IS TYPED.
^WHEN THIS OPERATION IS COMPLETED, <PIP AGAIN PROMPTS WITH THE
CHARACTER (*) TO INDICATED IT IS READY FOR THE NEXT COMMAND.
^TO <EXIT FROM <PIP, THE USER TYPES A ^CONTROL ^C (_^<C).
.PARAGRAPH
^ALL <PIP COMMANDS THAT TRANSFER DATA HAVE THE FOLLOWING GENERAL FORMAT:
.NOFILL.NOJUST
.SKIP 1
.CENTER
<DESTINATION __ <SOURCE(CR)
.SKIP 1
     ^THIS MAY BE EXPANDED AS FOLLOWS:
.SKIP 1
